        "additional_notes": "Once the project charter is signed, the project is formally authorized, and the project manager is empowered to begin planning activities—starting with identifying the individuals, groups, or organizations that may affect or be affected by the project. This step, known as the Identify Stakeholders process, is one of the most critical activities in the Initiating Process Group.\n\nDuring this process, the project manager gathers and documents detailed information about stakeholders, such as their interests, influence, involvement, communication needs, and expectations. Tools and techniques often used include stakeholder analysis, stakeholder mapping (e.g., power/interest grids or salience models), expert judgment, and reviewing enterprise environmental factors or organizational process assets.\n\nHowever, it is important to note that not every project activity related to stakeholders falls under this specific process. For example, developing stakeholder engagement strategies or planning how to manage stakeholder expectations is part of the Plan Stakeholder Engagement process, which occurs later in the Planning Process Group.\n\nThus, while identifying stakeholders, documenting their information, and analyzing their influence are core to the Identify Stakeholders process, developing engagement strategies is not—it is a forward-looking activity that follows after stakeholder identification and analysis are complete."
