        "additional_notes": "In complex IT projects that span multiple departments, identifying the right stakeholders early is essential to project success. Stakeholders influence project requirements, provide critical insights, and can significantly impact project outcomes through their level of support or resistance. Missing a key stakeholder can result in incomplete requirements, overlooked risks, or lack of buy-in—leading to delays or costly rework later in the project lifecycle.\n\nThe Identify Stakeholders process, conducted early in the Initiating phase, is designed to systematically recognize all individuals and groups affected by the project. To do this thoroughly, project managers should draw not only from stakeholder interviews and brainstorming sessions but also from Enterprise Environmental Factors (EEFs)—internal or external organizational elements that can influence project decisions.\n\nAmong the available EEFs, the organizational structure and existing stakeholder registers or historical information from previous similar projects are the most beneficial. These tools provide a starting point for identifying roles, departmental contacts, decision-makers, and subject matter experts. Past project records often include communication preferences, influence levels, and stakeholder engagement strategies that can be adapted to the current project.\n\nBy leveraging these organizational resources, the project manager improves stakeholder identification accuracy, promotes early alignment, and supports more effective engagement planning throughout the project."
